[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Q2. What evidence is there that citizen-centred approaches to public service design, delivery and choice of provider can deliver better outcomes—ensuring not only better value for money, but also greater social, economic and environmental value?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5. How successful have the Government’s reforms been in opening up public services to grassroots community groups, rather than to large private or third sector organisations?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Pre-procurement 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Source: NCVO public services and proc
[normal]urement survey 2013
[normal]________________________
[normal]1[bold]5[bold] A recent Public Administration Select Committee report into government procurement found that civil servants often lack an understanding about how to gather requirements, evaluate supplier capabilities, evaluate relationships or specify outcomes when procuring services and goods. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Procurement approaches 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Source: NCVO public services and procurement survey 2013 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]________________________
[normal]16[bold] A cost benefit analysis of one area found that with every £1 invested a return of £4.44 was achieved. When the benefits of improving quality of life are included, a return of £14.07 is gained for every £1 invested. 
[normal]17[bold] See NCVO’s report 
[normal]Open Public Services – Experiences from the Voluntary Sector for m
[normal]ore examples of pre-procurement dialogue producing better services 
[normal]http://www.ncvo.org.uk/images/documents/practical_support/public_services/open_public_services_experiences_from_the_voluntary_sector.pdf 
[normal]18[bold] The New Economics Foundation’s (NEF) report 
[normal]Doing Services Differently 
[normal]shows how some local authorities and providers are delivering better services by working in partnership with disabled people and disabled people’s organisations 
[normal]http://www.neweconomics.org/publications/entry/doing-services-differently
[normal]. 
[normal]19[bold] Large contracts excluding the VCS have been most visible in the Government’s flagship Work Programme. Organisations wishing to deliver one of 40 prime contracts had to display an annual turnover of at least £20 million and the financial capacity to deliver large contracts that require significant cash-flow. Consequently only three charities now act as a prime contractor. The 21 prime contracts for the 
[normal]MoJ’s
[normal] ‘Transforming Rehabilitation’ 
[normal]expects
[normal] organisations to have an annual turnover of between £6-36 million. 
[normal]That said, the effectiveness of large contracts at the local level is unclear
[normal]20
[normal] 
[normal]and many charities are unable to access the capital needed for these larger scale contracts, resulting in a diminution of local knowledge and expertise
[normal] 
[normal]21
[normal],22,23
[normal]. Large contracts can also create unnecessary layers of management and increased costs, as primes take a significant cut of contract value
[normal]24
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Social value 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Source: NCVO public services and procurement survey 2013 
[normal]________________________
[normal]20[bold] 
[normal]http://locality.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/Public-Services-Civil-Society-and-Diseconomies-of-Scale.pdf 
[normal]21[bold] A 2013 VCSE survey by Locality found that 42% of respondents believe contracts have become larger in the last five years and a further 52% expect them to become larger still over the next five years. 80% said this would provide them with less opportunities and a lower range and quality of services in their area. 
[normal]22[bold] A recent NCVO survey found that 23 out of 46 respondents said the scale of contracts has prevented their organisation bidding for work. One respondent noted how a county council have moved to county wide contracts rather than local ones, and that this has opened up the market to national providers to the detriment of local organisations. The full survey results can be provided on request. 
[normal]23[bold] The Federation of Small Businesses points out that the UK has amongst the largest average contract values in the EU. In France and Germany, with larger populations and similar size economies, average contract sizes are significantly smaller 
[normal]http://www.fsb.org.uk/policy/rpu/scotland/assets/publi_spec_procurabridjuly2012.pdf 
[normal]24[bold] An NCVO report The Work Programme – Perceptions and Experiences of the Voluntary Sector identifies management fees of between 15-20 percent 
[normal]http://www.ncvo.org.uk/images/documents/practical_support/public_services/SIG%20survey%202012%20report.pdf 
[normal]25 Ibid 
[normal]26[bold] A recent NPC report highlighted a case in Bradford where the City Council had reduced the number of homelessness services providers from 11 to 4, and required providers to demonstrate their financial strength while squeezing pricing. As a result, fewer VCS organisations bid for the contracts. 
[normal]http://www.thinknpc.org/publications/governance-in-the-new-commissioning-landscape/ 
[normal]27[bold] A recent survey by Compact Voice found that almost 90 percent of voluntary sector respondents believe that public bodies will still focus on lower cost rather than social value when funding 
[normal]http://www.compactvoice.org.uk/blogs/compact-voice/2013/08/07/local-compact-survey-results-2013-briefing-3-social-value 
[normal]28[bold] From NCVO members in two recent surveys. 
[normal]Also feedback from Compact Voice, the NCVO Public Services Delivery Network and other voluntary sector partners.
[normal] 
[normal]29[bold] One NCVO member reports how four years ago a public health body let a smoking cessation contract where the contract specification was 80 percent quality and 20 percent price. This year the contract was re-let at 60 percent price, 40 percent quality. 
[normal]30[bold] Good practice does exist. For its Café West Tender, York City Council held a number of events where they engaged with potential providers to discuss how social value should be built into the specification of the contact. Items in the specification included employing local people, working with people with disabilities and creating employment pathways. 
